docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:8:- `POST /api/v1/auth/login/`, `/refresh/`, `/logout/` with refresh rotation, replay rejection, revocation, auth audit events. Contracts in `docs/working/API_CONTRACTS.md`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:19:- Auth behavior moved behind explicit module functions in `sfpcl_credit/identity/modules/`: `tokens.py` (encode/decode/hash/claims + `TokenError`) and `auth_service.py` (`authenticate_user`/`CredentialError`, `issue_login_tokens_and_session`, `validate_refresh_session`, `rotate_refresh_token`, `revoke_session_for_logout`, `validate_access_token`, `record_auth_event`, `auth_payload`). Views are now thin (parse → call module → translate errors). `views.py` re-exports `TokenError` and `decode_token` for backward-compatible imports.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:20:- All 002B/002B2 behavior preserved (verified by unchanged `test_auth_api.py` + new `test_auth_module.py`): PyJWT HS256, lifetimes, claims, refresh rotation, replay rejection, logout revocation, inactive-user rejection, audit events.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:27:- Effective permissions come from `Permission.objects.filter(role_permissions__role=user.primary_role)`. Inactive primary roles return `[]`; A-007 zero-link roles (`sales_team_user`, `it_head`, `management_viewer`) return `[]` until source docs define grants.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:33:- Corrected `/api/v1/auth/me/` source fidelity before frontend shell wiring. The success `data` now includes `mobile_number`, `roles[{role_code, role_name}]`, and `teams[{team_code, team_name}]` in addition to the compatibility `role_codes`, `team_codes`, `permissions`, and `available_actions` fields.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:43:- 002D3 is DONE — `/auth/me/` now matches `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §11.4 while preserving 002D compatibility fields.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:45:- Architecture review 2026-07-03_170432 found no source-fidelity defect in the 002C/002C2 production behavior, but found two follow-ups:
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:56:- Source extracts for the 2026-07-03_224536 review: `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §11.4 defines `/auth/me/` profile + roles + teams + permissions; its closing implementation rule says React uses `available_actions` for UX while Django remains authoritative. `docs/source/implementation-roadmap.md` §10.6 says UI navigation must be role-aware and backend rejects unauthorized API calls. `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §13.1 includes role codes `it_head`, `internal_auditor`, `management_viewer`, and others that the frontend bridge must handle explicitly or neutrally.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:60:- 002EX completed the first real integration proof: minimal `tracer` Django app, one migration, session-bound `/api/v1/tracer/...` endpoints, service-layer transition guards, one audit log and one workflow event per transition, a staff-shell Tracer screen, and a narrow `tracer.lifecycle.run` permission bridge. Source extracts used: `api-contracts.md` §3 requires backend-enforced workflow, explicit action endpoints, auditability, versioned `/api/v1/`, and standard envelopes; `data-model.md` §26.1-26.2 defines append-only audit logs and workflow events. Browser screenshots remain deferred to 002EY because this sandbox blocked localhost binding with `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:67:- For 002G: build admin user/role management on the existing identity catalogue and `/auth/me/` serialization shape. Use `manage_users` as the explicit permission gate, standard envelopes/pagination, session-bound auth, existing `AuditLog`, and frontend navigation/page guard tests through the 002F shared navigation contract. Do not create free-text roles, teams, or permissions; bind only existing catalogue rows. Suspending a user must revoke active sessions; last-system-admin lock-out should be recorded in `ASSUMPTIONS.md` if source-doc-silent.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:70:- For 002G: save API examples for admin user list/detail/assignment plus `401`/`403`/validation/last-admin lock-out. If source docs still do not state the exact last-system-admin rule, record the selected guard in `ASSUMPTIONS.md` before coding and default to blocking any change that leaves zero active `system_admin` primary-role users. Add the admin user-management nav item and route to the same `allNavItems` / `PAGE_PERMISSIONS` / `visibleStaffNavItems` contract, requiring prototype `manage_users` from canonical `users.user.create|update|disable`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:71:- 002G completed admin user-management shell: backend routes under `/api/v1/admin/users/` list/detail users with the `/auth/me/` `roles[{role_code, role_name}]` and `teams[{team_code, team_name}]` shape, bind only existing active `Role`/`Team` rows, set status to `active`/`suspended`, audit role/team/status changes, and revoke active sessions when a user is suspended. Backend gate requires a session-bound active access token plus at least one canonical user-admin permission (`users.user.create`, `users.user.update`, `users.user.disable`); frontend maps those to prototype `manage_users` and adds `admin-users` to `allNavItems`, `PAGE_PERMISSIONS`, and the app route guard. A-014 records the source-silent last active `system_admin` guard: role/status changes that would leave zero active `system_admin` users return `400 VALIDATION_ERROR`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:72:- For 002H: keep the workflow guard foundation domain-neutral. A shared backend transition guard may define from-state, to-state, required permission, action code, and audit/workflow-event metadata, but must not encode loan eligibility, sanction authority, money amounts, or document-completeness rules. Migrate only the existing tracer transition proof to the shared guard and preserve its public endpoint behavior and `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION` / `403 PERMISSION_DENIED` envelopes.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:74:- 002H completed the shared workflow guard foundation. `sfpcl_credit/workflows/guard.py` defines domain-neutral transition definitions/results plus typed errors for unknown action, missing permission, and invalid state. Tracer services now pass explicit actor permission codes into the shared guard for lifecycle actions while preserving existing tracer URLs, success payloads, `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`, audit logs, and workflow events. No schema change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:80:- 002K2 corrected the guarded demo tracer grant after architecture review: `demo.tracer@sfpcl.example` now uses local/dev-only role `local_demo_tracer_user` with exactly A-011 `tracer.lifecycle.run`, while the shared source-catalogue `sales_team_user` role remains permission-neutral. Regression coverage creates a non-demo `sales_team_user`, reruns the guarded seed, logs in through `/auth/login/`, and verifies `/auth/me/` returns `permissions: []` and `available_actions: []`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:81:- Architecture review is due after 002K by cadence (`slices_completed_since_architecture_review` reaches 4). 003A has already been sharpened to add only a protected paginated `GET /api/v1/audit-logs/` over the existing `identity.AuditLog` model, using `audit.audit_log.read` as the narrowest existing audit-read permission. 003B has been sharpened to reconcile the pre-existing tracer-owned `workflow_events` table before creating/owning any canonical workflow-event foundation.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:92:- Role-to-permission matrix: §14.1 (high level), §15.1–15.12 (per-role detail — the seed data source).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:94:- Frontend already has a prototype permission model in `sfpcl-lms/src/contexts/RoleContext.tsx` (union `Permission`, `ROLE_PERMISSIONS`) — the seeded backend catalogue is the source of truth; the frontend union gets reconciled in 002D/002E.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:105:- `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §6.1 says success envelopes include `success`, `data`, and `meta.request_id`, `meta.timestamp`, `meta.api_version`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:107:- `docs/source/technical-architecture.md` §13.1 says Django views should not contain complex workflow orchestration; multi-entity operations, permissions, calculations, and audit logs belong in explicit service classes/functions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:108:- `docs/source/codebase-design.md` §6-7 says workflow/business logic should live behind explicit module interfaces and tests should exercise those interfaces, not scattered helpers.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:109:- Keep endpoint URLs and auth behavior unchanged: PyJWT HS256, token lifetimes, JWT claims, refresh rotation, replay rejection, logout revocation, inactive-user rejection, and auth audit events.
